XML_CASESUMMARY.SUMMARY:
This single vehicle crash occurred on a two lane, two-way divided asphalt roadway with a depressed median. There are two westbound and two eastbound lanes. This was a straight level, bituminous roadway with a posted speed limit of 120 kmph (75 mph). It was an early morning, the road was dry and the sky was clear.
Vehicle one (V1), a 2003 Pontiac Grand Am 4 door sedan driven by a 49 year-old male from an adjacent state with one passenger, was traveling eastbound in the number two lane The vehicle departed the left side of the road. The vehicle traveled off the roadway and then begun to rotate clockwise. The vehicle returned to the roadway in a northeasterly direction and traveled across both eastbound lanes. The vehicle began to rotate counterclockwise when it crossed the number one eastbound lane. It continued to rotate counterclockwise until it struck a speed limit sign off the right side of the roadway. The vehicle then rotated clockwise and began to travel in a southeasterly direction until the front struck a barbed wire fence. The vehicle struck the barbed wire fence a second time before it struck a large tree and came to rest facing in a northwesterly direction. The driver could not be located for an interview, although police reported the presence of alcohol consumption for this driver with no further information in this regard. The vehicle was towed due to damage.
The critical pre-crash event for V1 was coded: this vehicle traveling, off the edge of the roadway on the left side . The critical reason for the critical pre-crash event was coded as a driver related factor: type of driver error unknown. No interview was obtained with this driver, so the reason for the critical event could not be determined. Enviornmental and vehicle factors were ruled out based upon vehicle & scene inspections.
